he constellation is in a constant state of technological refresh. The company has transitioned from **V1 Broadband** satellites to currently deploying higher-throughput **V2 Mini** satellites. \n* **Next-Generation V3 Satellites (Upcoming Refresh/Expansion):** In the second half of 2026, the company plans to begin deploying next-generation **V3 satellites** via Starship. Each V3 satellite is designed to offer **1 Tbps of downlink capacity** (a massive leap in per-satellite capacity). Starship will be able to deploy up to 60 V3 satellites per launch, representing a 20-fold increase in deployed capacity compared to Falcon 9.\n* **End-of-Life Disposition:** When satellites reach the end of their useful life or are superseded by newer technology, they undergo controlled end-of-life disposition (such as safe deorbiting or transition to graveyard orbits where appropriate) to mitigate orbital debris risks. \n* **Hardware Repurposing (AI Compute):** For future orbital AI compute satellites (which evolve from the Starlink platform), the company plans to manage the refresh cycle by shifting older hardware to lower-intensity workloads as performance characteristics evolve before eventually retiring them.\n\n**Summary:** \nRather than a fixed time-based replacement schedule, Starlink\'s refresh cycle is driven by **propellant depletion, technological obsolescence, and generational leaps in capacity** (such as the impending shift to V3 satellites). The massive manufacturing cadence (~3,640 satellites/year) ensures that older satellites are continuously supplemented and replaced by newer, higher-capacity models.',
